00:34:24.880 --> 00:34:26.170
What if I impose that tax?

00:34:26.170 --> 00:34:28.870
Well, let's look at figure 22-3.

00:34:28.870 --> 00:34:33.440
What does that do to
the firm's decision, OK?

00:34:33.440 --> 00:34:34.940
Well, before the
government came in,

00:34:34.940 --> 00:34:37.380
the firm was
producing at point A

00:34:37.380 --> 00:34:39.130
where their private
marginal costs equaled

00:34:39.130 --> 00:34:40.588
the private marginal
benefit, which

00:34:40.588 --> 00:34:42.170
is the social marginal benefit.

00:34:42.170 --> 00:34:45.860
Now the government comes
in and levies a tax.

00:34:45.860 --> 00:34:49.903
It levies a tax at exactly
MD, the marginal damage.

00:34:49.903 --> 00:34:50.570
What does it do?

00:34:50.570 --> 00:34:53.300
It shifts their private
marginal cost curve

00:34:53.300 --> 00:34:56.290
to the social
marginal cost curve.

00:34:56.290 --> 00:35:00.240
It has caused the firm to
internalize the externality

00:35:00.240 --> 00:35:03.510
because now the firm is
paying an amount exactly

00:35:03.510 --> 00:35:06.790
equal to the damage
they're doing to society.

00:35:06.790 --> 00:35:10.710
So a corrective tax
can cause the firm

00:35:10.710 --> 00:35:14.090
to internalize the externality.

00:35:14.090 --> 00:35:18.128
Corrective tax caused the firm
to internalize the externality,

00:35:18.128 --> 00:35:18.960
OK?

00:35:18.960 --> 00:35:21.270
Essentially, a corrective
tax by the government

00:35:21.270 --> 00:35:24.420
can get us to the right
answer because it gets firms

00:35:24.420 --> 00:35:26.720
to do the right thing, OK?

00:35:26.720 --> 00:35:29.990
It gets firms to pay attention
to the social costs, not just

00:35:29.990 --> 00:35:31.340
the--

00:35:31.340 --> 00:35:34.345
not just the private costs.

00:35:34.345 --> 00:35:35.720
Similarly, we
could do same thing

00:35:35.720 --> 00:35:37.250
with a positive externality.

00:35:37.250 --> 00:35:40.950
What could the government do
with a positive externality?

00:35:40.950 --> 00:35:41.450
Yeah?

00:35:41.450 --> 00:35:42.350
STUDENT: Subsidize production.

00:35:42.350 --> 00:35:44.017
JONATHAN GRUBER: It
could subsidize by--

00:35:44.017 --> 00:35:48.380
so imagine I knew
exactly how much social

00:35:48.380 --> 00:35:51.500
benefit there was per unit
of R&D. If I subsidized

00:35:51.500 --> 00:35:55.560
the firm doing R&D, then I
would lower their costs, right?

00:35:55.560 --> 00:35:58.100
If I offered them a
subsidy of this amount,

00:35:58.100 --> 00:36:00.262
their cost curve
would shift down.

00:36:00.262 --> 00:36:01.220
I would lower the cost.

00:36:01.220 --> 00:36:04.110
So R&D would get
to the right point.

00:36:04.110 --> 00:36:07.100
So a corrective tax of
the amount of damage

00:36:07.100 --> 00:36:09.590
gets firms to internalize
the externality.

00:36:09.590 --> 00:36:12.020
A corrective subsidy
of that amount

00:36:12.020 --> 00:36:15.530
gets firms to internalize the
externality or individuals

00:36:15.530 --> 00:36:17.480
to externalize the internality.

00:36:17.480 --> 00:36:19.790
And we can get to
the optimal outcome

00:36:19.790 --> 00:36:22.160
by the government
imposing a corrective tax

00:36:22.160 --> 00:36:23.820
or subsidy of the right amount.

00:36:23.820 --> 00:36:26.360
Now we could of course also
get there with regulation.

00:36:26.360 --> 00:36:27.470
It's just a lot harder.

00:36:30.200 --> 00:36:32.410
Questions about that?

00:36:32.410 --> 00:36:37.490
OK, this is our first
example of good taxes, OK?

00:36:37.490 --> 00:36:40.490
Taxes have been bad
throughout this course.

00:36:40.490 --> 00:36:43.375
The role of taxes has been
distortionary to the economy.

00:36:43.375 --> 00:36:44.750
We haven't talked
about it a lot.

00:36:44.750 --> 00:36:46.792
We'll talk about it more
in a couple of lectures.

00:36:46.792 --> 00:36:48.840
They've been distortionary
to the economy.

00:36:48.840 --> 00:36:51.110
This is saying, no,
a tax can actually

00:36:51.110 --> 00:36:55.250
play a positive role because
a tax can correct a market

00:36:55.250 --> 00:36:57.120
failure.

00:36:57.120 --> 00:36:59.180
Now, as always, if the
tax is set incorrectly,

00:36:59.180 --> 00:37:00.748
it could make things worse.

00:37:00.748 --> 00:37:03.290
OK, if you set a tax that was
five times the marginal damage,

00:37:03.290 --> 00:37:04.887
it would make things worse.

00:37:04.887 --> 00:37:07.220
But, if you set it correctly,
it can make things better.

00:37:07.220 --> 00:37:09.553
We're offering the potential
for government intervention

00:37:09.553 --> 00:37:11.070
to make things better here.

00:37:11.070 --> 00:37:13.400
Questions about that?

00:37:13.400 --> 00:37:15.135
OK, so what do we have?

00:37:15.135 --> 00:37:17.260
We have a situation where
the private market is not

00:37:17.260 --> 00:37:21.120
delivering the optimal outcome.

00:37:21.120 --> 00:37:23.460
The private market is not
delivering the optimal outcome

00:37:23.460 --> 00:37:26.713
where it seems hard to
think of private solutions,

00:37:26.713 --> 00:37:29.130
but where a government solution,
either through regulation

00:37:29.130 --> 00:37:31.920
or easier corrective
taxation, can get us

00:37:31.920 --> 00:37:34.000
to the optimal outcome.

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:36.465
So now let's ask how does this
actually work in practice.

00:37:40.050 --> 00:37:41.760
And let's talk
about two examples.

00:37:41.760 --> 00:37:44.430
Let's talk about environmental
externalities and health

00:37:44.430 --> 00:37:45.700
externalities.

00:37:49.965 --> 00:37:51.590
Start with environmental
externalities.

00:37:51.590 --> 00:37:53.630
And, of course,
the most important

00:37:53.630 --> 00:37:56.685
is global warming, OK?

00:37:56.685 --> 00:37:59.060
Currently, the amount of carbon
dioxide in the atmosphere

00:37:59.060 --> 00:38:03.770
is at its highest
level in 400,000 years.

00:38:03.770 --> 00:38:06.380
Basically, every year becomes
the hottest year on record

00:38:06.380 --> 00:38:07.160
almost linearly.

00:38:07.160 --> 00:38:09.610
Almost monotonically, every year
is the hottest year on record.

00:38:09.610 --> 00:38:10.318
We're heating up.

00:38:10.318 --> 00:38:13.228
Scientists predict
that it's possible--

00:38:13.228 --> 00:38:15.020
the central prediction
is that temperatures

00:38:15.020 --> 00:38:19.072
will rise by more than 2 degrees
Fahrenheit by the end of the--

00:38:19.072 --> 00:38:20.780
I'm sorry, by more
than 2 degrees Celsius

00:38:20.780 --> 00:38:26.460
by the end of the century, but
it could be more than that.

00:38:26.460 --> 00:38:28.850
There's actually,
currently, the best estimate

00:38:28.850 --> 00:38:34.220
is that there's as
much as a 10% chance

00:38:34.220 --> 00:38:35.960
that temperatures
go up by 10 degrees

00:38:35.960 --> 00:38:37.543
by the end of the
century, which would

00:38:37.543 --> 00:38:40.400
end human life, basically,
in most of the world, OK?

00:38:40.400 --> 00:38:43.680
There is a non-trivial chance
we're all gone by 2100,

00:38:43.680 --> 00:38:46.190
not my problem, largely
not your problem,

00:38:46.190 --> 00:38:48.880
certainly your
kids' problem, OK?

00:38:48.880 --> 00:38:52.310
OK, by and large,
we are basically--

00:38:52.310 --> 00:38:55.375
we are basically-- we have a--
we know for sure there's going

00:38:55.375 --> 00:38:56.840
to be negative implications.

00:38:56.840 --> 00:38:59.630
Basically, we are essentially--

00:38:59.630 --> 00:39:02.590
unless there's a radical
new technology invented,

00:39:02.590 --> 00:39:03.920
Bangladesh is gone.

00:39:03.920 --> 00:39:05.180
It's over for Bangladesh.

00:39:05.180 --> 00:39:06.680
Cape Cod is gone.

00:39:06.680 --> 00:39:07.910
Much of Florida is gone.

00:39:07.910 --> 00:39:09.830
That's already happening, OK?

00:39:09.830 --> 00:39:12.080
At this point, the
question is can we actually

00:39:12.080 --> 00:39:15.200
stop the entire East and West
coasts and much of the South

00:39:15.200 --> 00:39:17.720
from disappearing as well
and many other countries

00:39:17.720 --> 00:39:20.360
in the world from
disappearing, OK?

00:39:20.360 --> 00:39:23.600
That's the sort of decision
we have to make now, OK?

00:39:23.600 --> 00:39:27.080
So, basically, this is a
classic negative externality

00:39:27.080 --> 00:39:28.825
because, that
negative situation,

00:39:28.825 --> 00:39:30.950
you were not thinking about
that when you filled up

00:39:30.950 --> 00:39:32.263
your car last time.

00:39:32.263 --> 00:39:33.680
You're not thinking
about the fact

00:39:33.680 --> 00:39:35.222
that the fossil
fuels you're emitting

00:39:35.222 --> 00:39:36.710
are contributing to that, OK?

00:39:36.710 --> 00:39:39.690
It's a classic
negative externality.

00:39:39.690 --> 00:39:41.060
So what can the government do?

00:39:41.060 --> 00:39:44.630
Well, the natural solution
would be corrective taxation.

00:39:44.630 --> 00:39:47.930
The natural solution would
be to have a carbon tax,

00:39:47.930 --> 00:39:50.570
to literally say this is
the amount-- we actually

00:39:50.570 --> 00:39:54.320
have a pretty good sense
from engineering models what

00:39:54.320 --> 00:39:59.030
the cost of carbon is, what the
marginal cost of carbon is, OK?

00:39:59.030 --> 00:40:01.190
And we could
literally impose a tax

00:40:01.190 --> 00:40:04.167
on the use of carbon
of that amount.

00:40:04.167 --> 00:40:05.750
I think it would
amount to something--

00:40:05.750 --> 00:40:06.860
I don't know the
numbers these days.

00:40:06.860 --> 00:40:09.230
It's something like between
$0.25 and $0.50 a gallon

00:40:09.230 --> 00:40:10.580
of gas.

00:40:10.580 --> 00:40:12.860
So it's a lot, but it's not--

00:40:12.860 --> 00:40:14.480
we've seen gas prices
in the last year

00:40:14.480 --> 00:40:16.200
go up and down by that much.

00:40:16.200 --> 00:40:19.168
OK, that's not an
outrageous amount, OK?

00:40:19.168 --> 00:40:20.960
In Europe, they already
have gasoline taxes

00:40:20.960 --> 00:40:23.510
well above that level, OK?

00:40:23.510 --> 00:40:27.923
So corrective taxation, in
principle, could be the answer.

00:40:27.923 --> 00:40:29.840
We could literally just
use engineering models

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:32.760
to compute the costs,
social costs of carbon.

00:40:32.760 --> 00:40:34.350
We could put a tax on it.

00:40:34.350 --> 00:40:37.740
And then at least we would stop
global warming going forward.

00:40:37.740 --> 00:40:39.370
You know, Bangladesh
may be gone,

00:40:39.370 --> 00:40:43.170
but we can maybe save a lot
of the rest of the world, OK?

00:40:43.170 --> 00:40:45.810
So that's in theory.

00:40:45.810 --> 00:40:48.390
In practice, in
1994, Bill Clinton

00:40:48.390 --> 00:40:53.040
proposed a $0.03 gas tax
and lost Congress, OK?

00:40:53.040 --> 00:40:56.550
In practice, people
don't like gas taxes.

00:40:56.550 --> 00:40:59.890
It's very hard politically
in the US and other places.

00:40:59.890 --> 00:41:03.220
And that is why the world has
turned to a different approach,

00:41:03.220 --> 00:41:05.310
which is quantity
regulation, which

00:41:05.310 --> 00:41:08.490
is say, look, in practice, we
should have a global carbon

00:41:08.490 --> 00:41:09.033
tax.

00:41:09.033 --> 00:41:10.950
In theory, we should
have a global carbon tax.

00:41:10.950 --> 00:41:11.992
In practice, that's hard.

00:41:11.992 --> 00:41:14.700
That's why we have negotiations.

00:41:14.700 --> 00:41:17.040
That's why we try to
have a global negotiation

00:41:17.040 --> 00:41:19.770
to try to get a global
cap on carbon emissions,

00:41:19.770 --> 00:41:23.445
actually have a quantity
regulation, to actually have

00:41:23.445 --> 00:41:25.110
a quantity regulation.

00:41:25.110 --> 00:41:25.860
We started this.

00:41:25.860 --> 00:41:27.510
The first true
global negotiation

00:41:27.510 --> 00:41:32.857
was in Kyoto, Japan
in December 1997.

00:41:32.857 --> 00:41:35.190
I was fortunate enough to be
there for that negotiation.

00:41:35.190 --> 00:41:37.260
I was in the Clinton
administration at the time.

00:41:37.260 --> 00:41:41.320
And we got to go over
and do that negotiation.

00:41:41.320 --> 00:41:43.320
It was actually pretty
neat because they decided

00:41:43.320 --> 00:41:44.850
I was going at the last
minute, and the only plane left

00:41:44.850 --> 00:41:45.975
to go on was Air Force Two.

00:41:45.975 --> 00:41:48.350
So I got to fly over with the
vice president on Air Force

00:41:48.350 --> 00:41:50.240
Two, which was pretty
cool, super cool.

00:41:50.240 --> 00:41:51.520
They have really
nice seats and stuff.

00:41:51.520 --> 00:41:53.562
And so I sat down, and
the phone next to me rang.

00:41:53.562 --> 00:41:54.517
And I was like--

00:41:54.517 --> 00:41:55.100
I answered it.

00:41:55.100 --> 00:41:55.640
I was like hello.

00:41:55.640 --> 00:41:56.640
They're like, hey, John.

00:41:56.640 --> 00:41:57.510
I'm like oh my god.

00:41:57.510 --> 00:41:59.610
It was them calling from
Japan, but like getting

00:41:59.610 --> 00:42:02.190
a personal phone call on
a plane was super cool.

00:42:02.190 --> 00:42:03.930
So, anyway, so I
went over to Kyoto.

00:42:03.930 --> 00:42:07.890
I learned how these negotiations
work, which is, over five days,

00:42:07.890 --> 00:42:10.440
I slept four hours.

00:42:10.440 --> 00:42:12.090
In Japan, they sell--

00:42:12.090 --> 00:42:14.020
they sold, at the time,
this coffee in cans.

00:42:14.020 --> 00:42:16.325
So you just chug these
cans of coffee all the time

00:42:16.325 --> 00:42:16.950
and stay awake.

00:42:16.950 --> 00:42:19.325
And, basically, everyone is
so tired by the end they just

00:42:19.325 --> 00:42:20.880
agree just to kind
of get it done.

00:42:20.880 --> 00:42:23.550
And that's sort of way
that negotiations work.

00:42:23.550 --> 00:42:25.590
So we agreed to the
Kyoto global warming

00:42:25.590 --> 00:42:28.660
treaty, which would have
lowered emissions worldwide,

00:42:28.660 --> 00:42:30.990
but the US did not sign on.

00:42:30.990 --> 00:42:33.438
The US refused to sign on.

00:42:33.438 --> 00:42:34.980
There's been continuing
negotiations.

00:42:34.980 --> 00:42:37.770
Most recently, we know about
the Paris round of negotiations,

00:42:37.770 --> 00:42:40.440
which the US did sign on to,
but the current administration

00:42:40.440 --> 00:42:42.420
has pulled us back out of.

00:42:42.420 --> 00:42:44.730
So we have a problem, which
is that, basically, we're

00:42:44.730 --> 00:42:47.160
heading to this
environmental catastrophe,

00:42:47.160 --> 00:42:52.380
and the world can't
agree on actions to take.

00:42:52.380 --> 00:42:57.000
And it's not really a choice.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:43:00.450
I mean, we have to do something,
or our grandkids will all

00:43:00.450 --> 00:43:02.580
be under water, or
our great-grandkids

00:43:02.580 --> 00:43:03.870
will all be under water.

00:43:03.870 --> 00:43:05.850
We have to do something.

00:43:05.850 --> 00:43:08.400
The optimistic case
that we'll do something

00:43:08.400 --> 00:43:11.220
comes from the example of what's
called chlorofluorocarbons.

00:43:11.220 --> 00:43:13.048
When I was a kid,
many, many products

00:43:13.048 --> 00:43:15.090
were made with what's
called chlorofluorocarbons.

00:43:15.090 --> 00:43:16.390
They were in refrigerators.

00:43:16.390 --> 00:43:19.440
They were in aerosol
sprays, et cetera.

00:43:19.440 --> 00:43:21.090
Scientists realized
they were actually

00:43:21.090 --> 00:43:23.040
damaging the ozone
layer, which protects us

00:43:23.040 --> 00:43:25.458
from ultraviolet
rays from the sun.

00:43:25.458 --> 00:43:27.000
And people were
like, yeah, whatever,

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:29.458
much like they are with global
warming now, yeah, whatever.

00:43:29.458 --> 00:43:32.550
But then a fucking hole
opened up in the ozone layer.

00:43:32.550 --> 00:43:34.710
Like, literally, it was
like, oh my god, there's

00:43:34.710 --> 00:43:36.090
a hole in the ozone layer.

00:43:36.090 --> 00:43:38.160
And 180 countries got
together almost overnight

00:43:38.160 --> 00:43:39.647
and banned chlorofluorocarbons.

00:43:39.647 --> 00:43:41.730
Like, literally, almost
overnight, they were gone.

00:43:41.730 --> 00:43:43.853
It was amazing,
international cooperation,

00:43:43.853 --> 00:43:45.270
terrific international
cooperation

00:43:45.270 --> 00:43:47.370
to take an environmental
catastrophe on and deal

00:43:47.370 --> 00:43:47.870
with it.

00:43:47.870 --> 00:43:49.662
The problem is global
warming doesn't quite

00:43:49.662 --> 00:43:50.790
work that way, OK?

00:43:50.790 --> 00:43:53.610
By the time we say, oh my god,
Bangladesh is under water,

00:43:53.610 --> 00:43:55.265
it's too late.

00:43:55.265 --> 00:43:56.640
So the question
is sort of how do

00:43:56.640 --> 00:43:58.553
we get politicians
and the public

00:43:58.553 --> 00:44:00.720
interested in taking something
on when we don't have

00:44:00.720 --> 00:44:03.060
the symbol, like a hole
in the ozone layer,

00:44:03.060 --> 00:44:06.600
to actually represent the
damage that's being done.

00:44:06.600 --> 00:44:09.360
And that is the challenge facing
something like global warming,

00:44:09.360 --> 00:44:12.450
but we have to take it on, OK?

00:44:12.450 --> 00:44:14.142
So that's environmental
externalities.

00:44:14.142 --> 00:44:15.600
The other big type
of externalities

00:44:15.600 --> 00:44:22.190
are health externalities,
are health externalities.

00:44:22.190 --> 00:44:26.660
I talked about smoking,
but, indeed, there

00:44:26.660 --> 00:44:29.090
are huge externalities levied
by a bunch of activities

00:44:29.090 --> 00:44:31.230
that we do that
impact our health.

00:44:31.230 --> 00:44:35.680
So, for example,
drinking, drunk driving

00:44:35.680 --> 00:44:40.730
causes 13,000 deaths per
year, 13,000 deaths per year,

00:44:40.730 --> 00:44:45.160
OK, to put a sort of blunt face
on it, four 9/11s every year

00:44:45.160 --> 00:44:49.750
from drunk driving plus
400,000 injuries every year

00:44:49.750 --> 00:44:52.540
from people driving drunk.

00:44:52.540 --> 00:44:57.910
Consuming gasoline, global
warming is a huge externality.

00:44:57.910 --> 00:45:00.370
Perhaps one of the biggest
externalities facing us,

00:45:00.370 --> 00:45:03.190
the biggest social
externality, is obesity, OK?

00:45:03.190 --> 00:45:06.400
Obesity causes a
lot of illnesses

00:45:06.400 --> 00:45:08.170
that cost a lot of money.

00:45:08.170 --> 00:45:10.930
Projections are that children
born in the year 2000,

00:45:10.930 --> 00:45:15.250
so about your kid, about your
generation, one third of them

00:45:15.250 --> 00:45:18.400
will get diabetes before they
die based on current weight

00:45:18.400 --> 00:45:19.260
projections.

00:45:19.260 --> 00:45:21.400
Now, as you notice,
looking around this room,

00:45:21.400 --> 00:45:24.900
that's not a problem of the
elite East Coast people, OK?

00:45:24.900 --> 00:45:27.400
It's not a problem of-- it's a
problem of the less educated.

00:45:27.400 --> 00:45:30.370
It's a problem concentrated
more in the South,

00:45:30.370 --> 00:45:33.910
but, nonetheless, if you look
at a number of southern states,

00:45:33.910 --> 00:45:36.970
the obesity rate is above 35%.

00:45:36.970 --> 00:45:39.670
Literally, more than one in
three people in the state

00:45:39.670 --> 00:45:41.530
are obese, OK?

00:45:41.530 --> 00:45:44.590
This is a huge problem, and it's
going to cause huge social--

00:45:44.590 --> 00:45:47.180
it's going to have huge social
consequences for our country.

00:45:47.180 --> 00:45:48.710
The question is what
do we do about these.

00:45:48.710 --> 00:45:50.877
What do we do about things
like smoking and drinking

00:45:50.877 --> 00:45:52.000
and obesity?

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:55.560
And there's essentially--
there's, essentially,

00:45:55.560 --> 00:45:57.160
four answers.

00:45:57.160 --> 00:46:00.310
The first is information.

00:46:00.310 --> 00:46:03.130
Can we just inform
people about the damages?

00:46:03.130 --> 00:46:06.970
And, indeed, this has been
shown to work with smoking.

00:46:06.970 --> 00:46:11.290
OK, we knew smoking was bad
for you in about 1954, OK?

00:46:11.290 --> 00:46:13.450
But we only really
got through to people

00:46:13.450 --> 00:46:16.610
starting really in
the 1970s and '80s,

00:46:16.610 --> 00:46:18.010
but it's had an enormous effect.

00:46:18.010 --> 00:46:19.940
Smoking has fallen
incredibly in the US

00:46:19.940 --> 00:46:21.110
through that information.

00:46:21.110 --> 00:46:23.230
But here's the
interesting thing, OK?

00:46:23.230 --> 00:46:27.297
Smoking rates-- smoking used
to be 50% in the entire--

00:46:27.297 --> 00:46:28.880
every adult, 50% of
all adults smoked.

00:46:28.880 --> 00:46:31.360
It didn't matter race,
gender, class, whatever.

00:46:31.360 --> 00:46:33.040
Now smoking is
essentially down to zero

00:46:33.040 --> 00:46:35.050
among the well-educated
and still about 20%

00:46:35.050 --> 00:46:36.760
against the less educated.

00:46:36.760 --> 00:46:39.580
So information
works, but it works

00:46:39.580 --> 00:46:42.950
in a very inequitable way.

00:46:42.950 --> 00:46:45.200
OK, so information
is one solution.

00:46:45.200 --> 00:46:47.830
The second solution is taxation.

00:46:50.490 --> 00:46:53.310
And, indeed, this has been shown
to work for cigarettes once

00:46:53.310 --> 00:46:55.190
again.

00:46:55.190 --> 00:46:57.250
Smoking is price sensitive.

00:46:57.250 --> 00:46:59.455
The elasticity of smoking
with respect to the price

00:46:59.455 --> 00:47:01.600
is about minus 0.4.

00:47:01.600 --> 00:47:04.300
About every 10% you raise
the price of cigarettes,

00:47:04.300 --> 00:47:06.160
there's about 4% less smoking.

00:47:06.160 --> 00:47:06.880
It works.

00:47:06.880 --> 00:47:10.890
In particular, youth smoking
is very price sensitive.

00:47:10.890 --> 00:47:13.610
Youths are very price sensitive
because youths have less money.

00:47:13.610 --> 00:47:16.570
So they're very price sensitive.

00:47:16.570 --> 00:47:18.940
So it actually works.

00:47:18.940 --> 00:47:20.348
But that's sort
of the easy case.

00:47:20.348 --> 00:47:22.390
Taxing cigarettes is easy
because every cigarette

00:47:22.390 --> 00:47:23.320
is bad for you.

00:47:23.320 --> 00:47:25.900
Taxing alcohol is trickier
because, after all,

00:47:25.900 --> 00:47:28.780
most of the damage is done
by a tiny share of drinkers.

00:47:28.780 --> 00:47:32.050
Most of us will consume alcohol
responsibly most of our lives

00:47:32.050 --> 00:47:34.072
and not cause any
external damage, OK?

00:47:34.072 --> 00:47:36.530
But most of the damage is done
by a tiny share of drinking.

00:47:36.530 --> 00:47:37.650
So taxes is trickier.

00:47:37.650 --> 00:47:39.400
If I proposed a big
rise in alcohol taxes,

00:47:39.400 --> 00:47:40.690
people would say wait a second.

00:47:40.690 --> 00:47:41.690
I'm responsible drinker.

00:47:41.690 --> 00:47:42.653
Why are you taxing--

00:47:42.653 --> 00:47:43.570
why are you taxing me?

00:47:43.570 --> 00:47:44.903
So that's a little bit trickier.

00:47:44.903 --> 00:47:46.480
Not to mention
obesity, taxing food

00:47:46.480 --> 00:47:48.580
is maybe the
trickiest of all, OK?

00:47:48.580 --> 00:47:50.850
So taxes are trickier.

00:47:50.850 --> 00:47:52.910
You could maybe try--

00:47:52.910 --> 00:47:55.320
an alternative thing you
could do is penalties.

00:47:55.320 --> 00:47:57.750
So, instead of
taxing alcohol, we

00:47:57.750 --> 00:48:00.327
could just steepen the
penalties for drunk driving.

00:48:00.327 --> 00:48:02.160
You know, if you killed
a few drunk drivers,

00:48:02.160 --> 00:48:04.620
there would be less
drunk driving, OK?

00:48:04.620 --> 00:48:07.050
But the problem is that's
a pretty extreme penalty.

00:48:07.050 --> 00:48:07.920
And what if you got it wrong?

00:48:07.920 --> 00:48:09.360
You'd feel kind of bad
about killing someone

00:48:09.360 --> 00:48:11.130
because the breathalyzer
didn't work.

00:48:11.130 --> 00:48:12.180
There was a series of
articles, actually,

00:48:12.180 --> 00:48:14.597
in The New York Times about
how terrible breathalyzers are

00:48:14.597 --> 00:48:16.590
and how inaccurate they are, OK?

00:48:16.590 --> 00:48:19.900
So problem with penalties is we
can't enforce them perfectly,

00:48:19.900 --> 00:48:20.640
OK?

00:48:20.640 --> 00:48:21.872
So that's the third solution.

00:48:21.872 --> 00:48:24.330
The final solution and the one
that's really most discussed

00:48:24.330 --> 00:48:28.050
right now is illegality.

00:48:28.050 --> 00:48:29.800
What if we just made
these things illegal?

00:48:29.800 --> 00:48:33.340
And this comes to the
discussion of marijuana.

00:48:33.340 --> 00:48:36.380
Should marijuana be legal, OK?

00:48:36.380 --> 00:48:42.350
Well, illegality is an extreme
form of lowering externalities.

00:48:42.350 --> 00:48:43.850
Now, obviously,
when pot is illegal,

00:48:43.850 --> 00:48:45.317
people still smoke pot.

00:48:45.317 --> 00:48:47.150
But it's still true,
when you make it legal,

00:48:47.150 --> 00:48:49.080
it's consumed at
much higher levels.

00:48:49.080 --> 00:48:50.880
OK, legality does matter.

00:48:50.880 --> 00:48:52.880
So, for example, people
have done studies.

00:48:52.880 --> 00:48:55.197
Yes, people under 21
drink, but, literally,

00:48:55.197 --> 00:48:57.530
if you look at people the day
after their 21st birthday,

00:48:57.530 --> 00:48:59.450
they drink much more than
the day before their 21st.

00:48:59.450 --> 00:49:01.242
Not on the 21st birthday,
that's the party.

00:49:01.242 --> 00:49:01.867
We ignore that.

00:49:01.867 --> 00:49:04.117
But, the day after their
21st birthday and thereafter,

00:49:04.117 --> 00:49:06.350
they're drinking at much
higher levels than before.

00:49:06.350 --> 00:49:08.303
Legality matters, OK?

00:49:08.303 --> 00:49:10.220
It's also true, the day
after a 21st birthday,

00:49:10.220 --> 00:49:12.428
people are much more likely
to die in a drunk driving

00:49:12.428 --> 00:49:15.680
accident than the day before
their 21st birthday, OK?

00:49:15.680 --> 00:49:17.280
So legality matters.

00:49:17.280 --> 00:49:18.890
So the point is we
have a whole series

00:49:18.890 --> 00:49:20.660
of tools to think about this.

00:49:20.660 --> 00:49:23.490
And the question is how should
we combine and use them.

00:49:23.490 --> 00:49:26.690
And the answer is
take 14.41, and I'll

00:49:26.690 --> 00:49:27.950
teach you all about it.

00:49:27.950 --> 00:49:29.510
But we don't any more time here.

00:49:29.510 --> 00:49:32.390
This just raises the issues to
think about with externalities.

00:49:32.390 --> 00:49:33.830
It's an important topic
to think about it.

00:49:33.830 --> 00:49:35.760
I realize that's a lot
to cover in one lecture,

00:49:35.760 --> 00:49:36.380
but I just wanted
to sort of give you

00:49:36.380 --> 00:49:38.300
a taste for how
economists think about

00:49:38.300 --> 00:49:41.050
and analyze this kind
of market failure.